        "response" : {
          "bodySize" : 98497,
          "content" : {
            "mimeType" : "application\/json",
            "size" : 98497,
            "text" : "{\"data\":[{\"id\":\"22cad68b-7033-4a1f-bc06-e07121a76a0b\",\"slug\":\"one-in-three-people-now-live-where-heat-blocks-activity\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.theguardian.com\/environment\/2026\/mar\/10\/extreme-heat-study-global-warming-physical-activity\",\"sourceTitle\":\"‘A sobering preview’: extreme heat now affects one in three people globally, study finds\",\"title\":\"One in three people now live where heat blocks activity\",\"titleLabel\":\"Liveability limits\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:07:22.895Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":8,\"relevance\":6,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"A new study combining physiological data and decades of climate and population records finds one-third of people now live where daytime heat severely restricts normal activity. Older adults face about 900 restricted hours a year (versus 600 in 1950), with poorest regions and outdoor workers hit hardest.\",\"quote\":\"a third of the world’s population now resides in areas where heat severely limits activity\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Original article\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Guardian reports a study finding one-third of people live where heat sharply limits activity; older adults lose ~900 safe hours yearly and poorer regions suffer most.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Global scale of exposure:** About one-third of the world now lives where heat severely limits daytime activity, a reach that qualifies as a significant, widely felt impact on health and daily life. This affects hundreds of millions of people across many countries and seasons. The mechanism is rising temperatures plus human physiological limits: when ambient conditions exceed safe thresholds people must reduce movement and exertion.\\n- **Worsening elderly vulnerability:** People over 65 now face roughly 900 hours annually of restricted outdoor activity, up from 600 hours in 1950, indicating a growing, sustained burden. This is a notable regional and demographic deterioration that raises health and care demands.\\n- **Unequal regional harms:** Low-income countries and hot tropical regions experience the worst limits, meaning the damages fall on populations that contributed least to emissions.\\n- **Labor and everyday functioning affected:** Limitations hit basic tasks and outdoor work, lowering productivity and mobility during hot hours.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Rising heat now restricts safe daytime activity for about one-third of people, adding hundreds of lost hours yearly for older adults and straining poorer regions.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Model and measurement uncertainty:** The study combines lab-based physiological thresholds with historical climate and population datasets, so results depend on assumptions about tolerance, exposure, and behavior; these introduce uncertainty about exact hours and affected populations. Replication and different threshold choices could change estimates.\\n- **Indoor adaptation and technology:** Air conditioning and other decent housing can substantially reduce harm for wealthier groups, so population-level effects are uneven and partly avoidable with infrastructure.\\n- **Single-study evidence:** Findings come from one published analysis; broader consensus or follow-up studies would strengthen confidence.\\n- **Focus on daytime summer activity:** The metric centers on peak daytime limitations and so does not capture wider health impacts across all seasons or indirect effects like migration.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"a16b6592-99fe-49a2-b128-4a23954cdf63\",\"title\":\"Guardian - Environment\",\"displayTitle\":\"Guardian \",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"}}},{\"id\":\"b3610e47-1191-4d01-9cca-6abb3169c193\",\"slug\":\"haitian-operations-kill-1-243-people-including-60-civilians\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/kathmandupost.com\/world\/2026\/03\/10\/hundreds-killed-in-haiti-drone-strikes-including-60-civilians-human-rights-watch-says\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Hundreds killed in Haiti drone strikes, including 60 civilians, Human Rights Watch says\",\"title\":\"Haitian operations kill 1,243 people, including 60 civilians\",\"titleLabel\":\"Drone strikes\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:04:58.774Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Human Rights Watch says Haitian security forces, aided by US-linked private contractor Vectus Global, used explosive quadcopter drones in Port-au-Prince, killing 1,243 people between March and January, including 60 civilians and many children. The strikes rose recently, caused fear and displacement, and HRW urges partners to stop cooperation until civilian safeguards exist.\",\"quote\":\"Haitian authorities should urgently rein in the security forces and private contractors working for them before more children die\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Juanita Goebertus, Human Rights Watch Americas director\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Kathmandu Post reports HRW says explosive drone attacks by Haitian forces and a US-linked contractor killed over 1,200 people, including 60 civilians, prompting urgent legal and policy scrutiny.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Mass civilian deaths and possible unlawful force:** HRW documents 1,243 people killed, including 43 adult civilians and 17 children, showing a serious breakdown in rules protecting civilians and law enforcement restraint. This is a major governance failure with strong regional humanitarian consequences. For example, more than half the child victims were 3-to-12-year-olds killed at a sports centre last September.\\n- **Private contractor involvement and state licensing:** A US-linked company, Vectus Global (led by Erik Prince), supported Haitian forces and the US State Department reportedly licensed its services, which complicates accountability and international legal norms. This raises significant policy and diplomatic questions about outsourcing lethal force and could prompt legal or regulatory responses from states and multilateral bodies.\\n- **Easily deployable explosive drone technology:** Quadcopter drones strapped with explosives and live video feeds can maneuver through dense urban areas, lowering the barrier to lethal operations in cities and increasing risk to bystanders.\\n- **Humanitarian and governance destabilization:** The strikes add to a crisis where gangs have killed thousands and displaced over a million people, making stabilization and civilian protection much harder.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Explosive drone strikes in Haiti killed over 1,200 people, eroding norms on the use of force and raising urgent legal and policy questions for states and contractors.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Primarily a national crisis:** The violence and strikes are concentrated in Haiti, so while severe they may not by themselves transform global governance or trigger broad international legal changes unless similar tactics spread to other states.\\n- **Report-based evidence and limited official investigation:** The main figures come from HRW and UN office reports, and BINUH said it saw no indications of investigations, which limits independent verification and immediate legal action.\\n- **Unclear chain of command and attribution:** The mix of national forces, a private contractor, and possible ad hoc decisions makes it hard to assign legal responsibility quickly, reducing the chance of near-term international policy consequences.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Global Governance Failure\",\"slug\":\"global-governance-failure\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"c7e2b91e-011a-4ac1-bf41-25a2a918181a\",\"title\":\"Kathmandu Post\",\"displayTitle\":\"Kathmandu Post\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"}}},{\"id\":\"936927bd-9c08-41b6-bf6c-0c4196a085d3\",\"slug\":\"us-navy-refuses-to-escort-ships-after-strait-attacks\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.channelnewsasia.com\/world\/iran-war-strait-hormuz-us-navy-escort-trump-oil-shipping-5985031\",\"sourceTitle\":\"US Navy tells shipping industry Hormuz escorts not possible for now\",\"title\":\"US navy refuses to escort ships after Strait attacks\",\"titleLabel\":\"Oil chokepoint\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:04:41.376Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":7,\"relevance\":6,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Since the Iran war began, the US Navy has declined repeated industry requests to escort ships through the Strait of Hormuz, saying attack risks remain too high. Shipping has largely stopped, blocking roughly a fifth of global oil exports, pushing prices up and raising the chance of wider military or economic fallout.\",\"quote\":\"the Strait is closed and Iran will fire on any ship trying to pass\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps senior official\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Channel NewsAsia\/Reuters reports the US Navy refused to escort ships through the Strait after attacks, halting roughly 20% of world oil exports and raising price and escalation risks.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Global oil supply disruption:** The halt of shipping through the Strait has effectively stopped exports that account for around a fifth of the world's oil, causing large price spikes and economic strain. This is a significant international economic disruption with immediate effects on fuel prices and trade. Because the Strait is a narrow chokepoint with few practical detours, stopped shipments quickly tighten markets and spread higher costs across supply chains.\\n- **Risk of military escalation between major powers:** The Navy's refusal to escort ships while Iran's Revolutionary Guards threaten to fire raises the chance of direct clashes and a broader regional confrontation. That combination of hostile threats and military postures fits a high-tension scenario that could drag in outside navies or allied responses.\\n- **Credibility gap in US security promises:** Public divergence between presidential statements and the Navy's on-the-ground assessment may weaken deterrence and complicate allied planning.\\n- **Supply chain vulnerability:** A brief regional conflict at a narrow waterway can immediately disrupt global trade, affecting refiners, shipping firms, and consumers worldwide.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"US Navy refusal to escort ships has halted about 20% of global oil exports, raising oil-price shocks and risk of wider military escalation.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Short, fluid timeline:** The conflict and shipping stoppage began a little over a week ago, so risk assessments and naval decisions can change rapidly. What looks like a sustained halt now may prove temporary if threats recede or escorts are later authorized.\\n- **Unverified and limited sourcing:** Reporting relies on unnamed industry sources and briefings with no immediate Pentagon comment, so details and permanence are uncertain.\\n- **Immediate impacts vs long-term change:** The story focuses on near-term price and shipping disruption rather than durable shifts in strategy or institutions, so lasting consequences are not yet proven.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"(Nuclear) War\",\"slug\":\"nuclear-war\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"d5034cae-73dc-41e0-ae98-e267ceffc8c1\",\"title\":\"Channel News Asia\",\"displayTitle\":\"CNA\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Science & Technology\",\"slug\":\"science-technology\"}}},{\"id\":\"f050d604-ddf5-44d6-b1b4-9367cc5f5005\",\"slug\":\"revolutionary-guards-install-new-supreme-leader-stir-regional-tensions\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.channelnewsasia.com\/world\/iran-new-supreme-leader-mojtaba-khamenei-revolutionary-guards-5985156\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Iran's new leader, still silent, was elevated by the Revolutionary Guards\",\"title\":\"Revolutionary Guards install new supreme leader, stir regional tensions\",\"titleLabel\":\"Iran succession\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:04:37.304Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":6,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Iran's Revolutionary Guards pushed Mojtaba Khamenei to become supreme leader, sidelining pragmatic clerics and politicians. Sources warn the Guards now hold decisive power, which could produce tougher foreign actions and harsher domestic repression. The new leader's silence and possible injury add uncertainty during an active war that has killed over a thousand Iranians.\",\"quote\":\"Mojtaba owes his position to the Revolutionary Guards and as such he is not going to be as supreme as his father was.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Alex Vatanka, senior fellow at the Middle East Institute\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Channel News Asia reports Iran's Revolutionary Guards pushed Mojtaba Khamenei to lead, boosting hardliners and raising risks of tougher foreign actions and harsher domestic repression.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Guard domination of succession and policy:** The Revolutionary Guards engineered Mojtaba Khamenei’s elevation and now appear to have decisive power, a change with significant regional consequences and implications for global diplomacy. This shifts Iran toward military-driven decision-making rather than clerical or civilian balancing, increasing the risk of escalation in conflicts the Guards manage. For example, Guards fury forced a presidential climbdown over apologies to Gulf states, showing they can overrule elected officials.\\n- **Higher risk of external aggression and proxy escalation:** Sources say a Guards-backed supreme leader is likelier to back hardline foreign operations, which can widen regional conflict and complicate international diplomacy. That raises the chance of more cross-border strikes, maritime threats, and clashes involving Israel, Gulf states, and US interests.\\n- **Domestic repression and legitimacy erosion:** A leader installed by the military risks harsher crackdowns at home and further weakening of the regime’s religious legitimacy.\\n- **Succession amid war and opacity:** The leader’s silence and possible injury create immediate uncertainty about command and control during an active war that has already killed over a thousand Iranians.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Guards-backed elevation of Mojtaba Khamenei strengthens military control, raising the likelihood of tougher external actions, stricter internal repression, and greater regional instability.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **High uncertainty and limited confirmation:** Much of the report relies on senior sources and state signals; key details (his condition, exact Guards role) are unverified. This uncertainty makes long-term impact projections tentative.\\n- **Primarily national\/regional scope:** The change directly affects Iran and its neighbors, not global institutions, so broader global governance effects are indirect and contingent on escalation.\\n- **Short-to-medium term unknowns:** Immediate effects depend on how other political factions and institutions respond; internal pushback could moderate outcomes.\\n- **Reporting and perspective limits:** The story is based on insider sources and external analysts, which can overemphasize military influence compared with quieter bureaucratic or clerical resistances.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Global Governance Failure\",\"slug\":\"global-governance-failure\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"d5034cae-73dc-41e0-ae98-e267ceffc8c1\",\"title\":\"Channel News Asia\",\"displayTitle\":\"CNA\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Science & Technology\",\"slug\":\"science-technology\"}}},{\"id\":\"bdfda137-845d-42e2-9803-1396a6587e6a\",\"slug\":\"china-builds-national-ai-grid-and-deprioritizes-chip-targets\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/thediplomat.com\/2026\/03\/chinas-5-year-plan-has-moved-beyond-the-chip-war-washington-hasnt-noticed\",\"sourceTitle\":\"China’s 5-Year Plan Has Moved Beyond the Chip War. Washington Hasn’t Noticed.\",\"title\":\"China builds national AI grid and deprioritizes chip targets\",\"titleLabel\":\"Computing strategy\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:04:19.097Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":6,\"emotionTag\":\"calm\",\"summary\":\"China’s 15th Five-Year Plan shifts focus from domestic chip production to an integrated 'model-chip-cloud-application' architecture. The government is building a national computing grid, policy-backed strategic computing reserves, and promoting overseas sovereign AI stacks, measuring success by digital-economy penetration rather than semiconductor self-sufficiency.\",\"quote\":\"China’s strategic objective is not the chip; it is the system that contains the chip.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Original article\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"The Diplomat reports China is shifting from chip-making to system-level AI infrastructure—creating a national computing grid, strategic reserves, and overseas AI stacks that could reshape supply chains and geopolitics.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **System-level strategic shift:** This reframing makes computing infrastructure the primary goal rather than just chipmaking, which is a significant change in national tech strategy and represents a substantial impact (high importance). The Plan creates a formal architecture—model, chip, cloud, application—that coordinates AI models, cloud services, and hardware across the economy. For example, the National Data Administration and NDRC have already issued standards and implementation guidance for a national computing grid and strategic reserves.\\n- **Policy to operationalize computing reserves:** China is not only renaming priorities but also issuing technical standards for resource pooling, unified scheduling, and crisis-override rules, moving planning into implementation, which is a notable, medium-to-high impact. This creates a mechanism to guarantee minimum computing services during supply shocks and to centrally allocate compute capacity.\\n- **Geopolitical diffusion via overseas deployments:** Chinese-built sovereign AI stacks are being installed abroad, showing real-world export of the system architecture and potential to extend influence over partner countries' AI infrastructure.\\n- **Economic reframing of success metrics:** Replacing a chip self-sufficiency target with a digital-economy value-added goal shifts incentives toward widespread deployment of computing services rather than producing more chips.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"China’s shift to national 'model-chip-cloud-application' systems could reshape AI infrastructure, affecting supply chains and geopolitical influence across dozens of partner countries by 2030.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Opinion\/analysis format:** The piece is an analytical article, not a primary government document or technical report, so some interpretation and emphasis reflect the author’s framing rather than objective measurement.\\n- **Uncertain scale and timeline:** Standards and pilot projects exist, but nationwide grid deployment and foreign uptake face technical, financial, and political hurdles that could slow or limit impact.\\n- **Persistent hardware constraints and sanctions:** Advanced chip fabrication still requires foreign tools and materials, and export controls could constrain China's ability to field cutting-edge hardware at global scale.\\n- **Single-project scale for some examples:** The Malaysia deployment cited is roughly $160 million, below the usual threshold for decisive global impact, so individual projects may not by themselves shift global tech balances.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Science & Technology\",\"slug\":\"science-technology\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"4cca3102-685e-498d-89bd-b244843bbc03\",\"title\":\"The Diplomat\",\"displayTitle\":\"The Diplomat\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Existential Threats\",\"slug\":\"existential-threats\"}}},{\"id\":\"3dcb4a85-1210-475a-b957-040bc4fb1d6c\",\"slug\":\"two-thirds-of-children-report-rising-online-harassment\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/news.un.org\/feed\/view\/en\/story\/2026\/03\/1167111\",\"sourceTitle\":\"An ‘alarming’ two-thirds of children say cyberbullying has increased\",\"title\":\"Two-thirds of children report rising online harassment\",\"titleLabel\":\"Cyberbullying\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:04:02.725Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":5,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"frustrating\",\"summary\":\"A UN poll of over 30,000 children finds around two-thirds say cyberbullying has increased and half don’t know how to get help. The report warns generative AI and deepfakes are accelerating and amplifying abuse, while stigma and poor reporting channels leave harms unresolved. The UN calls for governments, industry, educators and children to act together.\",\"quote\":\"AI deepfakes are increasingly used to humiliate, threaten and exploit children online\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Dr. Najat Maalla M'jid, UN Special Representative of the Secretary-General on Violence against Children\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"UN poll of 30,000+ children finds two-thirds say cyberbullying has increased; AI deepfakes and stigma amplify harms while half don't know how to get help.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Widespread child reports:** Around two-thirds of surveyed children across every region report rising cyberbullying, indicating a broad effect on children's personal safety and foundations of wellbeing. This scale suggests a moderate-to-widespread impact on children's daily lives and rights rather than a localized problem. The survey covered over 30,000 children, showing the trend crosses regions and platforms.\\n- **AI-enabled escalation:** The rapid spread of generative AI and deepfakes is described as fundamentally transforming threats by making attacks faster, more targeted and harder to detect. This represents an important technological change that increases the scale and severity of harm to children.\\n- **Barriers to help-seeking:** Half of children say they don’t know how to get the right support, so many harms go unreported and unresolved.\\n- **Acute mental-health and safety risks:** AI-amplified, public attacks can cause immediate psychological distress, reputational damage and, in tragic cases, push vulnerable children toward self-harm.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Rising cyberbullying and AI deepfakes threaten children's safety and mental health globally, likely affecting hundreds of millions and worsening help-seeking gaps.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Report and meeting framing:** The findings are presented in a UN report launched at the Human Rights Council, which is an advocacy and policy forum rather than a peer-reviewed scientific study. That context can amplify urgency but also means findings are framed to prompt action rather than settle causal questions.\\n- **Survey and perception limits:** The poll relies on self-reported experiences and perceptions, which can reflect heightened awareness as much as objective increases; sampling and cultural differences may affect comparability across regions.\\n- **No immediate policy or enforcement change:** The piece calls for coordinated action but does not describe new laws, funding commitments or platform safeguards yet, so near-term material change is uncertain.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Human Development\",\"slug\":\"human-development\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"56f76e77-509b-47ea-80bd-ba06b5bb66a1\",\"title\":\"UN - Peace and Security\",\"displayTitle\":\"UN\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Existential Threats\",\"slug\":\"existential-threats\"}}},{\"id\":\"1d8fa6e1-2086-4d6c-91c6-63f87eec9fc0\",\"slug\":\"israel-blocks-aid-leaving-pregnant-people-and-newborns-at-risk\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.aljazeera.com\/news\/2026\/3\/10\/women-in-gaza-denied-conditions-to-live-amid-israels-genocide-amnesty?traffic_source=rss\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Israel denies women in Gaza ‘conditions to live’: Amnesty\",\"title\":\"Israel blocks aid, leaving pregnant people and newborns at risk\",\"titleLabel\":\"Women's health\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:03:56.910Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Amnesty and UN agencies warn Israel's offensive in Gaza has destroyed health services, displaced hundreds of thousands and pushed women and girls to the brink. Pregnant people and newborns face higher risks from malnutrition, infection and lack of care, while aid and medical supplies remain severely restricted amid ongoing strikes.\",\"quote\":\"This systematic erosion of their rights to health, safety, dignity and a future is not an unfortunate by-product of war; it is a deliberate act of war targeting women and girls\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Amnesty International\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Al Jazeera reports Amnesty warns Israel's campaign has denied Gaza women safe conditions, wrecking healthcare and causing maternal and neonatal collapse for millions while raising regional tensions.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Mass civilian casualties and displacement:** More than 72,000 Palestinians killed and hundreds of thousands displaced create a large-scale humanitarian emergency that meets the 'significant impact' level in the criteria. The scale damages population health, infrastructure and social cohesion. For example, entire hospitals and clinics have been devastated and families forced into crowded displacement sites.\\n- **Collapse of maternal and neonatal care:** Gaza's health system has been devastated, producing rises in pre-term births, low-weight babies and maternal complications; UN OCHA says roughly 180 women give birth daily under constrained conditions. This is a major public-health shock that will increase short- and long-term mortality and morbidity among mothers and infants.\\n- **Humanitarian access restrictions:** Deliberate limits on aid, medical supplies and fuel are blocking lifesaving treatment and nutrition, directly worsening survival odds for pregnant people and newborns.\\n- **Regional escalation risk:** Continued attacks despite a ceasefire and references to Iran and US involvement raise the chance of wider regional tensions, which could amplify humanitarian and geopolitical consequences.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Gaza's war has killed 72,000+, wrecked health services, and is causing maternal and neonatal collapse for millions, raising regional tensions but not immediate nuclear risk.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Report and advocacy framing:** The piece mainly reports Amnesty's statement, which is an NGO report and advocacy document; such reports highlight harms but may emphasize one perspective. Independent verification and broader data sources are needed to fully assess scope and intent.\\n- **Limited relevance to nuclear or great-power strategy:** The story focuses on humanitarian and health collapse rather than changes in military doctrine or nuclear posture, so its direct bearing on global nuclear risk is limited.\\n- **Disputed or partisan data sources:** Some casualty and health figures come from local authorities and may be contested, which creates uncertainty about precise magnitudes.\\n- **Snapshot of an ongoing crisis:** The report describes severe but evolving conditions; long-term consequences depend on future political and military developments.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"(Nuclear) War\",\"slug\":\"nuclear-war\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"b8ce4d52-3eab-4dae-951d-e28dd93c2ee9\",\"title\":\"Aljazeera\",\"displayTitle\":null,\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"}}},{\"id\":\"d25b3a52-8dc8-40fd-96c8-f4f34f514942\",\"slug\":\"beijing-rolls-out-permissioned-blockchain-across-ministries-and-firms\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/asiatimes.com\/2026\/03\/939946\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Beijing’s blockchain push about trade, trust and control\",\"title\":\"Beijing rolls out permissioned blockchain across ministries and firms\",\"titleLabel\":\"Trust infrastructure\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:03:20.507Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":5,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"calm\",\"summary\":\"China is pushing permissioned, state-aligned blockchains as a domestic trust layer for trade, payments, records and administration. Beijing favors alliance chains and early regulation to keep data visible and controllable, and promotes Chang'an Chain as a domestic stack already deployed across ministries, SOEs and hundreds of thousands of firms.\",\"quote\":\"It is about building a state-compatible system for trusted data circulation under Chinese rules.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Original article\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Asia Times reports Beijing is building a state-controlled blockchain trust layer serving 300,000 firms and trillions of RMB; this reshapes trade data, standards and state oversight.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **State trust layer for trade and payments:** China is creating a blockchain layer meant to support high-value trade, finance and public administration rather than open crypto markets. This is a significant, infrastructure-level move with potential long-term economic impact because it directly touches how data and payments are verified across sectors. For example, Chang'an Chain is claimed to serve more than 300,000 cross-border firms and carry trade volumes in the trillions of renminbi, showing large-scale deployment intent.\\n- **Governability and state control:** Beijing designed this approach to make data flows visible and controllable, which fits a significant national-policy objective rather than an experimental technology push. That means the impact is primarily political and regulatory, shaping who can access and validate sensitive data across government and industry.\\n- **Domestic tech and standards autonomy:** The push drives China toward its own open-source stack and hardware acceleration, reducing reliance on foreign standards and components.\\n- **Cross-border trusted data spaces:** Official guidance links blockchain to privacy-preserving computing and cross-border trusted data, which could change how international trade data is shared and verified.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"China is building a state-run blockchain layer that already claims 300,000 firms and trillions of RMB in trade, shifting how trade data and digital trust are governed domestically.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Opinion\/analysis framing and reliance on official claims:** The piece is an explanatory analysis drawing heavily on government statements and numbers, so some claims (deployments, volumes) may be promotional rather than independently verified. This weakens confidence in how much is actually deployed versus announced.\\n- **Permissioned chains limit decentralization relevance:** The focus on alliance\/permissioned chains means this is more about state governance than the broader decentralizing promise of public blockchains, reducing its relevance to global crypto innovation.\\n- **Technical superiority not demonstrated:** Official metrics (code lines, chip cores, ministry deployments) show scale and intent but do not prove superior security, interoperability, or adoption outside China.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Science & Technology\",\"slug\":\"science-technology\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"0dd28b33-ea8f-442a-bc47-2f5755a98b6d\",\"title\":\"Asia Times\",\"displayTitle\":null,\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"}}},{\"id\":\"631be1e7-f2f1-47a9-9418-eda910b01705\",\"slug\":\"gauteng-sewage-contaminates-dams-that-supply-millions\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.dailymaverick.co.za\/article\/sewage-waste-and-failing-infrastructure-e-push-gautengs-rivers-toward-ecological\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Gauteng’s rivers pushed toward ecological collapse\",\"title\":\"Gauteng sewage contaminates dams that supply millions\",\"titleLabel\":\"River pollution\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:02:50.786Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":5,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Gauteng's rivers and some dams are heavily polluted with untreated sewage, industrial waste and toxic chemicals. Tests found unsafe levels of E. coli and other contaminants in many samples, threatening drinking water, public health and river ecosystems while failing wastewater plants and ageing infrastructure remain largely unaddressed.\",\"quote\":\"This is a noble ideal that has quite obviously not been applied to any distressed river in the country.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Anthony Turton, water management expert\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Daily Maverick reports Gauteng rivers carry untreated sewage and toxins into dams supplying millions, risking drinking water, public health and regional ecosystem collapse.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Contamination of major water supplies:** Rivers feeding the Vaal and other dams now carry sewage, heavy metals and algal blooms, putting drinking-water sources at regional risk; WaterCAN found 39 of 59 tested sources unsafe and E. coli in most river and all dam samples. This is a regional environmental and public-health problem that already affects water used by millions and could force costly emergency responses or water restrictions.\\n- **Failing wastewater infrastructure and governance:** Multiple wastewater treatment works and ageing sewers are not coping with urban waste and industrial runoff, a systemic failure in the four metros that is driving eutrophication and toxic algal growth. This represents a breakdown in basic services and water management with clear, ongoing ecological consequences.\\n- **Direct human exposure in daily life:** People use these waterways for washing, fishing and religious practice, raising immediate risk of infection and toxin exposure.\\n- **Ecosystem decline with downstream effects:** Algal blooms, invasive water lettuce and contaminants harm aquatic life and can spread through connected river systems, affecting fisheries and agriculture downstream.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Sewage and industrial waste are contaminating Gauteng rivers and dams, threatening drinking water and ecosystem health for millions in the region.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Regional scope:** The problem is severe in Gauteng and affects connected dams, but it is primarily a regional crisis rather than a global tipping point. While it threatens millions locally, it does not alone alter global climate or planetary-scale ecosystems.\\n- **Source and type of evidence:** The central data comes from a civil-society WaterCAN report and media sampling rather than peer-reviewed scientific publications, which raises questions about sampling methods and wider representativeness. This means findings are urgent but would benefit from independent, systematic testing.\\n- **Unclear national policy response and timelines:** The article documents failure and calls for action but provides little evidence of imminent large-scale investment or effective remediation plans, so the trajectory depends on future political and budgetary choices.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"4f199d9d-3d71-4816-ba3d-7ea285f55056\",\"title\":\"Daily Maverick\",\"displayTitle\":\"Daily Maverick\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Human Development\",\"slug\":\"human-development\"}}},{\"id\":\"0cfd3f37-f4da-4e44-81c8-f5ee605ae87d\",\"slug\":\"us-weighs-tanker-escorts-risking-clashes-with-iran\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.al-monitor.com\/originals\/2026\/03\/mideast-tanker-escort-high-risk-mission-us-navy\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Mideast tanker escort: high-risk mission for US Navy\",\"title\":\"US weighs tanker escorts, risking clashes with Iran\",\"titleLabel\":\"Strait security\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:02:03.206Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":7,\"relevance\":6,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"U.S. leaders have discussed Navy escorts for tankers through the Strait of Hormuz to keep crude flowing, but escorts would face layered threats — mines, drones, missiles and fast boats — that make the mission risky and resource-intensive and could raise regional tensions.\",\"quote\":\"If you put mines in the water and you can reinforce those with both surface and air threats as well, you create a layered threat that extends from under the sea all the way up through the surface into the air\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Jonathan Schroden, chief research officer, Center for Naval Analyses\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Al-Monitor reports U.S. plans to escort tankers through the Strait of Hormuz could protect roughly 20% of global oil flows but risk mine, missile and drone clashes with Iran and regional escalation.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Global oil flow disruption:** Escorting tankers through the Hormuz directly affects nearly 20% of the world’s crude, so any interruption is a major economic shock and a significant international security issue; this is a high-impact, potentially escalatory scenario rather than a minor incident. The narrow channel and high traffic mean an attack or mining could quickly halt shipments and spike prices, as seen in multiple reported strikes between March 1–10. The mechanism is straightforward: damage or blockade in the strait would choke supply routes and ripple through global markets.\\n- **Risk of military escalation between the U.S. and Iran:** A U.S. escort mission is likely to increase direct contact between American and Iranian forces, raising the chance of clashes that could broaden into wider conflict; this represents a significant regional escalation risk. Iran’s public threats and past attacks increase the odds that escorting convoys would draw kinetic responses.\\n- **Modern Iranian tactics and weapons:** Iran’s access to mines, missiles, drones and fast-attack craft raises the danger level above past escort missions and makes defenses harder to guarantee.\\n- **Strain on U.S. naval resources:** Escorting slow commercial tankers would be resource-intensive, diverting destroyers, frigates, aircraft and logistics from other tasks and increasing exposure to attacks.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"U.S. tanker escorts through the Hormuz could threaten roughly 20% of global oil flows and raise the risk of regional military clashes, though action is not yet taken.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Proposal not yet executed:** The discussion of escorts is still at the planning\/threat level, so the most severe outcomes are hypothetical and depend on future decisions and actions. This uncertainty means immediate global catastrophe is unlikely unless the mission actually begins and an incident occurs.\\n- **News reporting and expert commentary:** The article compiles expert warnings and recent incidents but does not present new operational orders or confirmed escalatory events, which reduces the strength of causal claims about what will happen next.\\n- **Limited nuclear risk:** While the situation raises regional war risks, nothing in the reporting indicates an increased likelihood of nuclear use; the threat is conventional and economic rather than nuclear in nature.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"(Nuclear) War\",\"slug\":\"nuclear-war\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"8277b133-44f3-4621-b831-f5efaa7a65e7\",\"title\":\"Al-Monitor\",\"displayTitle\":\"Al-Monitor\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Human Development\",\"slug\":\"human-development\"}}},{\"id\":\"bcfca217-4e31-4840-be0f-a5a0c5f7bd62\",\"slug\":\"senator-says-us-may-send-forces-into-iran\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.middleeasteye.net\/news\/democratic-senator-says-trump-path-toward-deploying-us-troops-iran\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Democratic senator says Trump on 'path toward deploying' US troops in Iran\",\"title\":\"Senator says US may send forces into Iran\",\"titleLabel\":\"Troop deployment\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:01:47.377Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":8,\"relevance\":6,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"After a classified Senate briefing, Senator Richard Blumenthal warned the Trump administration appears likely to send U.S. forces into Iran. Reuters reports at least 150 U.S. troops wounded and eight killed so far. Democrats say the president has not sought congressional authorization, while the White House defends keeping options open and cites preventing a nuclear threat.\",\"quote\":\"We seem to be on a path toward deploying American troops\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Richard Blumenthal, Democratic U.S. Senator from Connecticut\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Middle East Eye reports Senator Richard Blumenthal warned the US is 'on a path' to send forces into Iran; reported casualties and alleged Russia\/China support raise wider war risks.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Potential US ground deployment:** If the United States actually sends forces into Iran, this would be a major escalation with a high chance of widening the conflict and drawing in regional and global powers; this matches the higher-impact band of the criteria because it could trigger sustained, large-scale fighting; Senator Blumenthal’s warning is a direct signal that policy may be moving toward that outcome.\\n- **Scale of casualties so far:** Reuters reports at least 150 U.S. troops wounded and eight confirmed dead, which shows the conflict has already produced meaningful U.S. losses and fits a moderate-to-significant impact level; rising casualties raise domestic pressure for either escalation or withdrawal and can change political calculations rapidly.\\n- **Great power involvement:** Allegations that Russia and China are aiding Iran increase the risk of a broader geopolitical confrontation and complicate de-escalation.\\n- **Lack of congressional authorization and unclear objectives:** The administration’s failure to seek Congress’s approval and to state clear goals weakens legal and political constraints on action and can make escalation more likely.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"U.S. signals toward sending forces into Iran, with 150 wounded and eight dead reported, raising risk of wider regional war though reports remain unverified.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Unverified public claims:** The core warning comes from a senator’s interpretation of a classified briefing and Reuters cites unnamed sources, so key details and official plans are unconfirmed and may change.\\n- **Partisan and rhetorical context:** Statements come amid intense partisan debate, which can amplify worst-case framings for political effect rather than reflect settled policy.\\n- **No public operational order:** The president has not publicly announced a plan or objective for an occupation or invasion, and some diplomacy (Oman-mediated talks) was reported as nearing agreement, reducing the immediate certainty of ground invasion.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"(Nuclear) War\",\"slug\":\"nuclear-war\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"96cfec65-20ee-4f55-99f0-3ebb9d616780\",\"title\":\"Middle East Eye\",\"displayTitle\":\"Middle East Eye\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Human Development\",\"slug\":\"human-development\"}}},{\"id\":\"88c3103a-be98-4482-82e3-da5665294f42\",\"slug\":\"yann-lecun-startup-secures-890-million-seed-funding\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.heise.de\/news\/Weltmodell-statt-LLM-Start-up-von-Yann-LeCun-erhaelt-890-Millionen-Euro-11206213.html?wt_mc=rss.red.ho.ho.atom.beitrag.beitrag\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Weltmodell statt LLM: Start-up von Yann LeCun erhält 890 Millionen Euro\",\"title\":\"Yann LeCun startup secures €890 million seed funding\",\"titleLabel\":\"World models\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-11T01:00:33.386Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"calm\",\"summary\":\"Yann LeCun's Paris-based startup AMI Labs raised €890 million in seed funding from major investors including Nvidia, Samsung, Toyota and Jeff Bezos. The company will pursue 'world models'—AI that understands and reasons about the real world—targeting industry, biomedicine and robotics, but practical applications may take years.\",\"quote\":\"We share a conviction: true intelligence does not begin with language. It begins in the real world\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"AMI Labs (company web page)\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Heise reports Yann LeCun's AMI Labs raised €890M to build 'world models' instead of LLMs, attracting major investors; it accelerates research but practical uses may take years.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Massive seed funding and high-profile backers:** This €890 million round is unusually large for an early-stage AI startup and brings major industry players and prominent investors on board, which can quickly expand resources and hiring. That scale makes the effort a potentially significant accelerator of AI research in Europe and beyond. For example, AMI Labs grows from a dozen employees to a much larger team using these funds, increasing research throughput and influence.\\n- **Strategic shift toward world models instead of LLMs:** The company explicitly aims to build models that understand the real world and support memory, reasoning and planning, which could materially change the technical direction of some AI research. If successful, this approach could reduce risky hallucinations in domains like medicine.\\n- **Targeting safety-critical industries:** Planned partnerships in industry, biomedicine and robotics mean advances could affect systems where errors matter, like clinical tools or factory robots.\\n- **Concentration of top AI talent and credibility:** Founders include Yann LeCun and former Meta leaders, which attracts talent and steers research priorities across the field.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"LeCun's AMI Labs secured €890 million to build world-model AI, boosting research capacity and influence but remaining early with likely years before broad impact.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Very early-stage research with a small team:** AMI Labs currently has only about a dozen employees and admits that much basic research is still needed, so commercial or wide effects are likely years away. The timeline and technical feasibility are highly uncertain.\\n- **Funding does not guarantee a breakthrough:** Large investment accelerates work but does not ensure world models will outperform current systems in practice.\\n- **Competing efforts exist:** Other startups and big labs (e.g., World Labs, Meta, Google) are pursuing similar ideas, so any single firm's influence may be diluted.\\n- **Company-specific product focus:** This is a single-company effort, so broader effects depend on successful partnerships and open scientific contributions.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Artifical Intelligence\",\"slug\":\"artificial-intelligence\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"3a110c9f-9803-441d-afcf-3f2337f73b87\",\"title\":\"Heise\",\"displayTitle\":null,\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Science & Technology\",\"slug\":\"science-technology\"}}},{\"id\":\"f315ec86-7f6c-4450-8024-70c4b3d4eb56\",\"slug\":\"west-bengal-places-6-million-people-under-adjudication\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/thediplomat.com\/2026\/03\/purging-millions-from-west-bengals-voters-list-risks-disenfranchisement\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Purging Millions From West Bengal’s Voters List Risks Disenfranchisement\",\"title\":\"West Bengal places 6 million people under adjudication\",\"titleLabel\":\"Electoral roll\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:03:50.381Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"frustrating\",\"summary\":\"A Special Intensive Revision of West Bengal's electoral roll removed 540,000 names and placed about 6 million of 70.8 million electors under adjudication. The process used new categories and automated checks that disproportionately called Muslims for hearings, caused widespread stress for voters and officials, and shrank the final list by 16 percent.\",\"quote\":\"The new roll does not contain 540,000 names \\u0003effectively struck off\\u0003 and has placed an additional 6 million names ... under adjudication.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Original article\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"The Diplomat reports West Bengal's draft voters list strikes 540,000 names and puts 6 million under adjudication, raising minority disenfranchisement and AI-bias concerns.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Scale of disenfranchisement and political risk:** The draft roll removes 540,000 people and puts about 6 million of 70.8 million electors under adjudication, a large, concentrated change that can alter election outcomes and representation; this is a major regional governance failure with potential national political effects. The mechanism is administrative list revision combined with mass adjudication hearings that can temporarily or permanently block voting. For example, the final list shrank 16 percent and districts with higher Muslim populations show disproportionate adjudication rates.\\n- **Disproportionate impact on minorities and electoral fairness:** Local analyses show Muslims were overrepresented in the 'Logical Discrepancy' and adjudication lists, suggesting bias in who faces removal or hearings; this represents a significant threat to inclusive democracy at the state level. Targeting marginalized groups in voter rolls undermines trust in electoral institutions and could change who wins tight races.\\n- **Administrative collapse and human cost:** The exercise caused severe stress on Booth Level Officers and voters, with reported suicides and overwhelmed staff, showing institutional strain that weakens election administration. Overworked officials and missed hearings can produce chaotic implementation.\\n- **Algorithmic mismatch and procedural opacity:** Use of AI-driven 'Logical Discrepancy' categories produced errors from name abbreviations and data mismatches, creating wide uncertainty for millions and opaque decision rules.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"West Bengal's roll removed 540,000 names and put 6 million of 70.8 million electors under doubt, risking minority disenfranchisement and electoral distortion.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Regional scope and uncertain national spread:** The exercise is concentrated in one Indian state (albeit populous) and its practices may not automatically scale nationwide; the final consequences depend on how the state and Election Commission resolve adjudications. This reduces the immediate global governance significance.\\n- **Single-news reporting and interpretive analysis:** Coverage and cited local research point to troubling patterns but rely on draft lists and correlational analysis, so causality (intentional targeting) is not fully proven. That leaves some findings provisional rather than definitive.\\n- **Ongoing process with changing outcomes:** The numbers cited come from a draft and adjudication phase; final lists, appeals, or legal challenges could restore many names, changing the ultimate scope of disenfranchisement. This uncertainty limits long-term impact assessment.\\n- **Local political context may confound patterns:** Links between adjudication rates and party margins suggest politicization, but local administration, data quality, and historical roll errors could also explain disparities, so evidence of deliberate nationwide strategy is incomplete. \",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Global Governance Failure\",\"slug\":\"global-governance-failure\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"4cca3102-685e-498d-89bd-b244843bbc03\",\"title\":\"The Diplomat\",\"displayTitle\":\"The Diplomat\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Existential Threats\",\"slug\":\"existential-threats\"}}},{\"id\":\"faae80d1-6d8b-4579-8d8a-35e90b68b142\",\"slug\":\"mojtaba-khamenei-named-iran-s-top-authority\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.aljazeera.com\/video\/newsfeed\/2026\/3\/9\/what-to-know-about-irans-new-supreme-leader-mojtaba-khamenei?traffic_source=rss\",\"sourceTitle\":\"What to know about Iran’s new Supreme Leader Mojtaba Khamenei\",\"title\":\"Mojtaba Khamenei named Iran's top authority\",\"titleLabel\":\"Succession\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:02:40.624Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-11T02:15:00.800Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Mojtaba Khamenei, son of the late Ali Khamenei, has been named Iran’s Supreme Leader during a period of mass unrest and economic turmoil. His accession concentrates power and will influence how Iran uses repression, conducts regional proxy policy, and engages in nuclear negotiations, with important but uncertain effects on regional diplomacy.\",\"quote\":\"The son of slain Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei will now be charged with leading Iran through the biggest crisis in the Islamic Republic’s modern history.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Original article\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Al Jazeera reports Mojtaba Khamenei has become Iran’s supreme leader. His succession concentrates power for tens of millions and could shift regional diplomacy and nuclear talks, though global effects remain uncertain.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Political succession and regime stability:** Mojtaba Khamenei’s rise centralises authority at the top of Iran’s theocratic state and will determine how the government responds to protests and economic collapse, which is a significant national development with regional consequences. This affects tens of millions of Iranians who live under the regime and rely on state services. The mechanism is straightforward: a new supreme leader sets security priorities, appoints key commanders, and can change domestic repression and succession norms, for example reshaping the balance between hardline and pragmatic factions.\\n- **Foreign policy orientation and regional security:** The new leader’s outlook and ties to the IRGC and allied militias could shift Iran’s stance toward neighbours, maritime routes, and proxy conflicts in Lebanon, Syria, Iraq, and Yemen. That is a regional-scale impact that can alter negotiations, sanctions dynamics, and the risk of cross-border incidents.\\n- **Domestic legitimacy and protest dynamics:** A hereditary-style transfer within the Khamenei family may inflame domestic opposition and sustain protests, making internal repression and instability likelier in the near term.\\n- **International diplomacy and sanctions response:** Western and regional governments are likely to reassess diplomatic engagement and sanctions strategies, which affects international coordination over nuclear talks and regional de-escalation.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Mojtaba Khamenei’s succession concentrates power affecting tens of millions and regional diplomacy, including nuclear talks, though wider global governance effects remain uncertain.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Uncertain authority and elite support:** It is unclear how much real power Mojtaba Khamenei immediately holds or whether Iran’s military, clerical establishment, and security services will fully back him, so long-term policy shifts are speculative. This uncertainty weakens claims about immediate global governance consequences.\\n- **Explainer format and limited analysis depth:** The Al Jazeera piece is a news explainer rather than a detailed policy study, so it informs public understanding more than it provides new evidence of systemic change.\\n- **Primarily regional impact:** Most direct effects will be inside Iran and across the Middle East; global institutions and long-term governance are affected only if unrest or policy choices trigger wider crises or major diplomatic breakdowns.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Global Governance Failure\",\"slug\":\"global-governance-failure\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"b8ce4d52-3eab-4dae-951d-e28dd93c2ee9\",\"title\":\"Aljazeera\",\"displayTitle\":null,\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"}}},{\"id\":\"9db1e6a8-d41e-4fd7-8293-afeaa7d8b080\",\"slug\":\"three-year-average-reaches-1-5-c-above-preindustrial-levels\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/e360.yale.edu\/digest\/warming-gaining-pace\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Global Warming Is Accelerating, Study Shows\",\"title\":\"Three-year average reaches 1.5°C above preindustrial levels\",\"titleLabel\":\"Global warming\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:06:54.183Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":8,\"relevance\":7,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"A new study finds the planet's warming rate has accelerated: the last three years average about 1.5°C above preindustrial levels. Atmospheric CO2 is at multi-million-year highs, emissions keep rising, and forests and other carbon sinks are weakening. The study warns a likely breach of the Paris 1.5°C limit by around 2030, raising tipping-point risks.\",\"quote\":\"Together, the past three years measured 1.5 degrees C warmer than the preindustrial era, putting the world at least temporarily in breach of a key target of the Paris Agreement.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Original article\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Yale Environment 360 reports three-year global temperatures reached 1.5°C above preindustrial levels; weakened carbon sinks and rising emissions make a Paris 1.5°C breach likely by about 2030.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Acceleration of global temperature:** The recent rise — 0.35°C per decade over the last ten years and a three-year average at 1.5°C above preindustrial — represents a significant to exceptional climate shift that affects billions through heat, storms, and sea-level rise. This is classed as a high-impact development because it increases the chance of crossing dangerous climate thresholds. For example, the study projects a likely Paris 1.5°C breach by about 2030, shortening the window for emissions cuts.\\n- **Breakdown of carbon sinks and feedbacks:** Forests and other natural sinks are degrading from fire and drought and are shifting from absorbing carbon to releasing it, which is a serious multiplier on warming. This feedback increases the scale and pace of warming beyond emissions alone, moving the situation toward a significant, long-term climate challenge.\\n- **Paris 1.5°C exceedance and tipping-point risk:** A sustained breach of 1.5°C would sharply raise the risk of triggering ecosystem tipping points such as Amazon dieback or permafrost thaw, with global consequences.\\n- **Rising emissions and reduced aerosol masking:** Continued increases in fossil-fuel emissions plus cleaner air (fewer cooling aerosols) are together accelerating warming, making near-term policy inaction more costly.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Three-year global temperatures hit 1.5°C above preindustrial levels, increasing tipping-point risks and making a Paris 1.5°C breach likely by around 2030 without faster emissions cuts.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Short-term versus long-term threshold measurement:** The reported 1.5°C is based on a three-year average, while the Paris target uses a 20-year average, so the exceedance may be temporary. This makes the immediate policy and legal implications less certain.\\n- **Single new study in a crowded field:** While published in a peer-reviewed journal, this is one study among many; scientific consensus moves on the weight of multiple studies and assessments, so conclusions should be confirmed by further analysis.\\n- **Media summary format:** The piece summarizes scientific results for a general audience rather than presenting raw data, which reduces technical detail needed to fully assess uncertainty.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"7a8aff2f-bef3-4139-9029-200af2f6353f\",\"title\":\"Yale Environment 360\",\"displayTitle\":\"Yale E360\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"}}},{\"id\":\"7c0a7fd4-039f-4698-8595-fc2a7c022038\",\"slug\":\"gulf-stream-jumps-north-decades-before-atlantic-current-collapse\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/phys.org\/news\/2026-03-shift-gulf-stream-collapse-major.html\",\"sourceTitle\":\"How a shift in the Gulf Stream could signal the collapse of a major ocean current system\",\"title\":\"Gulf Stream jumps north decades before Atlantic current collapse\",\"titleLabel\":\"AMOC risk\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:05:25.174Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":8,\"relevance\":6,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Researchers used high-resolution ocean models and observational records to show the Gulf Stream can jump about 219 km north roughly 25 years before an Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC) collapse. Satellite and deep-sea data already show a northward drift, suggesting the AMOC may be weakening and could approach a tipping point sooner than thought.\",\"quote\":\"These findings provide indirect evidence for present-day AMOC weakening and demonstrate that abrupt Gulf Stream shifts can serve as an early warning indicator for AMOC tipping.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"René M. van Westen et al., study authors\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"phys.org reports high-resolution models and observations show a northward Gulf Stream shift can precede AMOC collapse by ~25 years, signaling faster tipping risk with regional climate consequences.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **AMOC collapse risk:** The study links a sudden Gulf Stream jump to an eventual AMOC shutdown, indicating a pathway to a major climate tipping point; this is classified as a significant-to-exceptional impact because an AMOC collapse would strongly alter regional climates and ocean heat transport. The mechanism is freshwater-driven slowdown that destabilises the conveyor-belt circulation, and in the model the shift preceded collapse by about 25 years, implying rapid downstream effects on weather and marine systems.\\n- **Gulf Stream as early warning signal:** The modeled 219 km northward jump appears roughly 25 years before collapse, making the Gulf Stream a measurable precursor rather than a simultaneous symptom; this raises the finding to a moderate-to-significant real-world relevance because a clear physical warning increases detection and response options. Detectable shifts in current position could be tracked by satellites and deep-ocean sensors to give decades of lead time.\\n- **Observed northward drift:** Real-world satellite and deep-sea records show the Gulf Stream moving north from Cape Hatteras, matching the model precursor and suggesting present-day weakening is already measurable.\\n- **Improved high-resolution modeling:** The use of fine-scale ocean simulations reveals abrupt shifts that coarser models miss, strengthening confidence in identifying tipping behavior and informing climate risk assessments.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"A northward Gulf Stream shift may foreshadow AMOC collapse, risking major climate shifts in the North Atlantic and Europe and altering ocean heat for millions over decades.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Model dependence and scenario design:** The main result comes from a simulation where freshwater was steadily added to force collapse, an idealized scenario that may not match real-world melt rates or pathways. This means the timing and abruptness seen in the model could be faster or slower than reality.\\n- **Observational ambiguity:** The detected northward drift and weakening signals are indirect and can reflect natural variability, longer-term cycles, or measurement limits, so they do not yet prove imminent collapse.\\n- **Uncertain timeline:** Even if the mechanism is real, the collapse could take decades to centuries, so near-term societal impacts are uncertain and depend on how fast forcing increases.\\n- **Regional versus global effects:** The most severe climate impacts would be regional (North Atlantic, Europe), not uniformly global, which narrows the immediate human impact compared with worldwide catastrophes.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"07de1fb2-591d-4082-bd11-4ff3b90e2301\",\"title\":\"phys.org - Editorials\",\"displayTitle\":\"phys.org\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Science & Technology\",\"slug\":\"science-technology\"}}},{\"id\":\"c9faf801-6f9f-4a1b-a29d-c82d0d2d9d8a\",\"slug\":\"middle-east-fighting-stops-20-of-daily-oil-shipments\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.channelnewsasia.com\/world\/iran-war-oil-prices-middle-east-5982956\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Oil prices swing wildly as Iran war threatens transport routes and production across Middle East\",\"title\":\"Middle East fighting stops 20% of daily oil shipments\",\"titleLabel\":\"Hormuz routes\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:04:52.484Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":7,\"relevance\":6,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Fighting linked to the Iran war has disrupted oil production and tanker traffic across the Middle East, briefly pushing Brent and WTI above US$119 before a market reversal. Tankers largely avoided the Strait of Hormuz, halting about 15 million barrels daily and forcing producers to cut output and burn storage capacity, risking weeks of tight global supplies and higher prices.\",\"quote\":\"In economic terms, this is already the largest oil supply shock ever\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Nicholas Mulder, assistant professor of history who studies economic impacts of wars, Cornell University\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Channel NewsAsia reports fighting around Iran has halted tanker traffic through key routes, threatening about 15 million barrels daily and risking weeks of higher global oil prices.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Strait of Hormuz stoppage:** Tanker traffic through the Strait has all but stopped, threatening roughly 15 million barrels a day and creating a major global supply shortfall; this is a significant international shock that matches high-impact events in energy markets. The mechanism is direct: attacks and the threat of missile and drone strikes make transit too risky, so ships avoid the passage and shipments fall. For example, Gulf producers have cut exports and some declared force majeure because storage is full and tankers will not pass the strait.\\n- **Widespread production cuts and storage constraints:** Several Gulf producers (Iraq, Kuwait, UAE, Bahrain) are reducing output and running out of storage, which amplifies the crisis beyond transport and raises the chance of sustained shortages. This is a high, region-wide disruption that could persist for weeks as restarting output and moving stored oil is a technical, time-consuming task.\\n- **Global price shock and economic ripple effects:** Prices spiked above US$119 a barrel and could rise toward US$150 if disruptions last, which would raise fuel costs and inflation in many countries.\\n- **Damage to energy and civilian infrastructure:** Strikes on refineries, depots and a desalination plant show the conflict is hitting both energy supply and essential services, increasing humanitarian and recovery costs.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Regional fighting threatens 20% of daily oil shipments, producing a major supply shock that risks weeks of higher prices and global economic strain.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Duration uncertainty:** Markets have already shown rapid reversals (prices fell under US$90 after a US political comment), so the supply shock could be short-lived if attacks ease; that makes long-term economic impacts uncertain.\\n- **News-report snapshot:** This is a news story describing unfolding events rather than a policy change or confirmed long-term trend, so its long-run governance implications are not yet established.\\n- **Competing forecasts:** Some analysts (Oxford Economics) expect prices to moderate to about US$80 a barrel this quarter, indicating plausible scenarios where disruption is temporary and economic effects are limited.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Global Governance Failure\",\"slug\":\"global-governance-failure\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"d5034cae-73dc-41e0-ae98-e267ceffc8c1\",\"title\":\"Channel News Asia\",\"displayTitle\":\"CNA\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Science & Technology\",\"slug\":\"science-technology\"}}},{\"id\":\"ab90a861-c8ae-4457-931b-d3808d4b0ad7\",\"slug\":\"europe-buys-far-more-weapons-ukraine-tops-import-list\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/en.mercopress.com\/2026\/03\/09\/global-arms-trade-rose-in-2021-25-as-european-demand-surged\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Global arms trade rose in 2021-25 as European demand surged\",\"title\":\"Europe buys far more weapons; Ukraine tops import list\",\"titleLabel\":\"Arms trade\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:04:22.086Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":7,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"SIPRI data show global transfers of major weapons rose 9.2% in 2021–25, driven by a 210% surge in European imports. Ukraine was the single largest importer (9.7%). The United States increased exports to Europe, while Russia's exports fell sharply, shifting supplier power and regional military balances.\",\"quote\":\"Most other European states have also started importing significantly more arms to shore up their military capabilities against a perceived growing threat from Russia\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Mathew George, director of SIPRI's Arms Transfers Programme\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Merco Press reports SIPRI data showing European weapons imports jumped 210% in 2021–25 and Ukraine was the top buyer at 9.7%. This signals major regional rearmament affecting hundreds of millions and shifting exporter power.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **European rearmament surge:** European imports jumped 210%, making Europe the largest importing region and prompting NATO members to rebuild stockpiles; this is a significant international shift affecting hundreds of millions of people across Europe and neighboring regions. The surge is largely driven by deliveries to Ukraine and wider perceived threats from Russia, creating a sustained demand for major weapons. That demand fuels longer-term military preparedness, procurement planning, and defense industry expansion across many states.\\n- **Ukraine as top buyer:** Ukraine accounted for 9.7% of global major arms imports in 2021–25, reflecting an active, high-intensity conflict that sustains large-scale weapons flows; this has immediate humanitarian and security consequences for tens of millions in and around Ukraine. Continued high imports indicate prolonged conflict dynamics and dependency on external suppliers for battlefield needs.\\n- **US export dominance shift to Europe:** The United States increased its export share to 42% and sent a larger share to Europe (38%), strengthening US influence over European militaries and supply chains and shaping alliance politics.\\n- **Supplier landscape changed by Russia's collapse:** Russia's exports fell 64%, shrinking its market share and opening opportunities for other exporters (Germany, France, Israel, South Korea), which alters geopolitical leverage and future conflict sponsorship patterns.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"A 210% rise in European weapons imports and Ukraine’s 9.7% share signal major regional rearmament affecting hundreds of millions and shifting exporter power balances.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Descriptive data, not causal evidence:** SIPRI reports transfers but does not show how weapons change battlefield outcomes or political decisions; reliable data still leave open whether increased deliveries shorten or prolong conflicts. This limits how directly the numbers translate to long-term global impacts.\\n- **Aggregate five-year totals mask timing and weapon types:** The dataset compresses deliveries over five years and does not detail which weapon systems were transferred, so the security implications depend heavily on what was delivered and when.\\n- **Regional rather than global effect:** Most changes measure shifts within Europe and a few regions, so many billions of people worldwide are only indirectly affected by altered supplier balances.\\n- **Missing non-state and small-arms details:** The focus on major arms omits small arms and non-state actor flows that also drive violence in many countries, reducing the completeness of the picture.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"ab317554-0028-4fd6-b913-62beaf234ee8\",\"title\":\"Merco Press\",\"displayTitle\":null,\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"}}},{\"id\":\"6def3f1a-aad5-4444-898e-9dab1bfd7eaf\",\"slug\":\"zelenskyy-offers-low-cost-interceptors-to-help-regional-allies\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.aljazeera.com\/news\/2026\/3\/9\/what-defence-support-could-ukraine-offer-middle-east-states-amid-iran-war?traffic_source=rss\",\"sourceTitle\":\"What defence support could Ukraine offer Middle East states amid Iran war?\",\"title\":\"Zelenskyy offers low-cost interceptors to help regional allies\",\"titleLabel\":\"Air warfare\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:02:48.902Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"calm\",\"summary\":\"Ukraine has offered to provide low-cost interceptor drones, technical expertise and civilian support to Middle Eastern states and US forces defending against Iranian Shahed drones. Kyiv proposes exchanging its counter-drone technology for advanced US systems, which could ease pressure on costly interceptor missiles even as political, logistical and scale uncertainties remain.\",\"quote\":\"Ukrainians have been fighting against ‘shahed’ drones for years now, and everyone recognises that no other country in the world has this kind of experience. We are ready to help\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Volodymyr Zelenskyy, President of Ukraine\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Al Jazeera: Zelenskyy offered Ukraine's low-cost interceptor drones and expertise to help Middle East states against Iranian Shahed attacks; this could ease costly US interceptor use but faces political and logistical limits.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Ukraine air-defence transfer and tech exchange:** Ukraine offering mass-produced, low-cost interceptor drones and know‑how in exchange for advanced US systems could shift defensive capacity across two wars and represents a major development in military support and strategy. This is a moderate-impact change in military dynamics because it creates a cross-theatre exchange of hardware and expertise that can change how allies are defended. For example, Kyiv might trade thousands of $1,000–$2,000 interceptors for access to Patriot or THAAD batteries, altering who can sustain long air-defence campaigns.\\n- **Drone warfare and cost asymmetry:** The spread of cheap Iranian Shahed loitering munitions and Ukraine's counter-drone designs create a technology race that changes battle economics; this counts as a moderate-impact change in military capabilities. Ukraine's experience intercepting many Shahed-type attacks provides practical know-how that is directly transferable to Gulf defence needs.\\n- **Strain on US interceptor stocks:** Relying on Patriot and THAAD missiles to shoot down low-cost drones is expensive and can deplete limited interceptor inventories, so Ukraine's cheaper systems could materially reduce ammunition and logistics pressure.\\n- **Risk of wider escalation:** Moving hardware, training, or personnel between the Russia and Iran theatres could entangle partners and complicate alliances, increasing the chance of broader confrontation.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Ukraine offering low-cost interceptor drones and expertise could reduce Gulf defence costs and ease US missile use, but political, logistical and scale limits constrain impact.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Political and logistical hurdles:** Weapon and system transfers require US approval, export controls, basing rights, training and sustainment arrangements, so plans could stall or be scaled down quickly. These steps usually take months and depend on political will and legal clearances.\\n- **No confirmed deals or numbers yet:** The coverage reports offers and requests but not finalized transfers, so immediate operational impact is uncertain.\\n- **Integration limits:** Ukraine's low-cost interceptors are proven in its own context but may not plug easily into Gulf air-defence architectures or stop long‑range missile threats.\\n- **Defensive intent reduces some risk:** These are mostly defensive measures intended to protect bases and infrastructure, which is less likely to trigger direct offensive escalation than new offensive deployments.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"(Nuclear) War\",\"slug\":\"nuclear-war\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"b8ce4d52-3eab-4dae-951d-e28dd93c2ee9\",\"title\":\"Aljazeera\",\"displayTitle\":null,\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"}}},{\"id\":\"0fdebb3b-1871-4f91-ba38-c039f15c1400\",\"slug\":\"trump-says-he-s-not-happy-after-tehran-names-khamenei-s-son\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.aljazeera.com\/news\/2026\/3\/9\/trump-slams-mojtaba-khameneis-appointment-as-iran-projects-defiance?traffic_source=rss\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Trump slams Mojtaba Khamenei’s appointment as Iran projects defiance\",\"title\":\"Trump says he's 'not happy' after Tehran names Khamenei's son\",\"titleLabel\":\"Iran succession\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:02:37.279Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":7,\"relevance\":7,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"After the US and Israel killed Iran's supreme leader, Tehran's Assembly of Experts named his son Mojtaba Khamenei as successor. President Trump said he was \\\"not happy\\\" and had tried to influence the choice. The appointment is framed as defiance amid a widening regional war that has killed over 1,250 people and disrupted oil shipping.\",\"quote\":\"I\\u00039m not going through this to end up with another Khamenei. I want to be involved in the selection.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Donald Trump, President of the United States\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Al Jazeera reports Tehran named Mojtaba Khamenei after US\\nnd Israeli strikes killed his father. The move deepens a regional war, raises escalation risks and disrupted oil shipping.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Scale of regional war and casualties:** The conflict described includes thousands of strikes and more than 1,250 deaths, making it a large, multi-front regional war rather than a limited skirmish. This aligns with a significant-impact scenario that could spill over into wider fighting. For example, Iran\\nnd allied groups have launched hundreds of missiles and drones, and fighting now involves Israel, Hezbollah and US assets.\\n- **Direct US involvement and political targeting:** The United States and Israel carried out a joint strike that killed Iran's supreme leader, and the US president has publicly tried to influence Iran's succession and called for its \\\"unconditional surrender.\\\" This hardens geopolitical stances and raises the risk of escalatory policy choices and direct interventions by major powers, which fits a scenario with substantial geopolitical consequences.\\n- **Raised nuclear and large-scale conflict risk:** Rhetoric about targeting leadership and the presence of major powers on opposing sides increases the chance of miscalculation that could broaden the war or prompt more extreme responses.\\n- **Global energy and trade disruption:** Attacks have hit energy infrastructure and largely closed the Strait of Hormuz, a key oil shipping lane, driving oil prices sharply higher and threatening economic impacts for millions worldwide.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Mojtaba Khamenei's appointment amid US\\nnd Israeli strikes deepens a regional war, threatens wider escalation, disrupts oil shipping, and affects millions of people.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Rapidly changing situation and uncertainty:** Events are unfolding and many decisions have yet to be taken by key actors, so outcomes and long-term effects remain highly uncertain. The current picture could change quickly if diplomacy, internal politics, or military moves shift.\\n- **Single news report and emphasis on statements:** The piece mainly reports speeches and reactions rather than new policy changes or verified strategic shifts, so it documents rhetoric more than binding actions.\\n- **Rhetorical escalation vs. concrete policy:** Much of the danger cited comes from inflammatory language and calls for targeting, which do not always translate into implemented strategies or lawful state policy.\\n- **No confirmed nuclear employment or doctrinal change:** While risk is higher, there is no evidence here of nuclear use or official doctrine changes that would indicate an immediate, higher-tier nuclear crisis.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"(Nuclear) War\",\"slug\":\"nuclear-war\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"b8ce4d52-3eab-4dae-951d-e28dd93c2ee9\",\"title\":\"Aljazeera\",\"displayTitle\":null,\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"}}},{\"id\":\"6035997e-04bb-4353-b79d-709b784657c6\",\"slug\":\"trump-says-iran-campaign-very-soon-as-oil-tops-100\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.al-monitor.com\/originals\/2026\/03\/trump-says-iran-war-end-very-soon-oil-prices-soar\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Trump says Iran war to end 'very soon' as oil prices soar\",\"title\":\"Trump says Iran campaign 'very soon' as oil tops $100\",\"titleLabel\":\"Middle East war\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:02:28.793Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":7,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"The US has carried out thousands of strikes in Iran over ten days, with President Trump saying the campaign has made major gains but could continue. The conflict has closed the Strait of Hormuz, pushed oil above $100 per barrel, displaced hundreds of thousands regionally, and raised the risk of wider regional escalation.\",\"quote\":\"We could call it a tremendous success right now, or we could go further, and we're going to go further.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Donald Trump, President of the United States\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Al-Monitor reports Trump claims major gains in the Iran campaign while warning more strikes; oil tops $100 and Strait of Hormuz closures threaten global markets and regional stability.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Regional conflict and civilian harm:** The fighting has displaced nearly 700,000 people in Lebanon and caused combat across the Gulf, which is a significant humanitarian and security impact that meets criteria for major regional disruption. The strikes and retaliatory attacks are collapsing local services and forcing mass movements of people. For example, attacks have hit oil facilities and populated areas, worsening shelter and personal safety for many.\\n- **Energy supply shock:** Closure of the Strait of Hormuz and repeated attacks have pushed oil above $100, creating a significant global economic shock that affects energy costs and living expenses worldwide. This is a broad economic impact that can slow growth and increase prices for hundreds of millions of people.\\n- **Risk of wider military escalation:** US statements about holding targets for later (including electricity infrastructure) increase the chance of prolonged conflict and infrastructure damage that would harm basic services.\\n- **Political hardening in Iran:** Appointment of Mojtaba Khamenei as supreme leader signals a harder line in Tehran, likely prolonging hostility and reducing prospects for a quick political resolution.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"The Iran–US conflict has closed key oil routes and displaced hundreds of thousands, driving oil above $100 and risking wider regional and economic disruption.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Claims vs. independent verification:** Many key assertions (e.g., ‘everything they had is gone’) come from political leaders and are hard to verify in real time, so the true military and civilian effects may be overstated or misunderstood. This makes it difficult to assess long-term consequences until independent counts and damage assessments are confirmed.\\n- **Early-stage and fluid situation:** The conflict is only ten days old and still evolving, so trajectories (de-escalation, wider war, or negotiated pause) remain uncertain and affect how broadly people will be harmed.\\n- **News framing and political spin:** Statements by the US president and officials are partly aimed at domestic audiences and deterrence, which can exaggerate immediacy or success and reduce the article's predictive reliability.\\n- **Local vs global effects distinction:** While oil markets react globally, direct humanitarian harms remain concentrated regionally for now, limiting immediate impacts on basic needs for most of the world's population.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Human Development\",\"slug\":\"human-development\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"8277b133-44f3-4621-b831-f5efaa7a65e7\",\"title\":\"Al-Monitor\",\"displayTitle\":\"Al-Monitor\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Human Development\",\"slug\":\"human-development\"}}},{\"id\":\"0b3ea5ec-6aeb-40f8-af06-852cf2c87899\",\"slug\":\"iran-escalates-missile-and-energy-attacks-to-wear-down-foes\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.al-monitor.com\/originals\/2026\/03\/analysis-iran-bets-endurance-energy-disruption-outlast-us-israel\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Analysis-Iran bets on endurance, energy disruption to outlast US, Israel\",\"title\":\"Iran escalates missile and energy attacks to wear down foes\",\"titleLabel\":\"Endurance strategy\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:02:24.778Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":8,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Iran is pursuing a war-of-attrition strategy: the IRGC runs operations, backing Mojtaba Khamenei's rise, while using missiles, drones and energy-route attacks to pressure the US, Israel and regional economies. Observers warn Iran may sustain strikes for weeks, testing Western political will and risking prolonged regional disruption to energy markets and governance.\",\"quote\":\"For them, they are waging an existential fight. This is an all-out war\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Fawaz Gerges, professor of international relations, London School of Economics\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Al-Monitor\/Reuters reports Iran, led by the IRGC, is using missiles, drones and energy-route strikes to wear down the US and Israel; that risks weeks of regional disruption and higher global energy prices.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Attrition through energy disruption and strikes:** Iran is deliberately targeting energy hubs and shipping routes to drive up costs and politically wear down the US and its allies; this is a significant-impact development that could escalate regional instability and test major powers' resolve. The mechanism is economic pain: higher energy prices and disrupted supply chains raise domestic pressure in the US, Europe and Gulf states. For example, strikes on Gulf energy nodes and shipping could quickly raise oil and gas prices and strain allied political support for sustained military action.\\n- **IRGC control and domestic consolidation:** The Revolutionary Guards now direct battlefield operations and played a decisive role in elevating Mojtaba Khamenei, increasing the Guards' political power and making Iran's response more centralized and risk-acceptant; this represents moderate-to-high impact on how decisions are made and sustained. A more dominant IRGC raises the chance Iran will prioritize regime survival and prolonged confrontation over de-escalation.\\n- **Missile and drone campaign duration:** Iran may still retain a large share of pre-war missile stocks, meaning strikes could continue for several weeks and prolong the crisis.\\n- **Global market and supply-chain vulnerability:** Attacks on Gulf energy infrastructure and shipping can quickly disrupt global fuel and commodity markets, transmitting economic pain to Europe, Asia and the United States.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Iran's campaign to grind down opponents with missile strikes and energy disruption raises the risk of a prolonged regional war and sustained global energy shocks for weeks.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Analysis piece with sourced claims:** This is an interpretive analysis relying on unnamed regional sources and insiders, so some claims (stockpile size, internal dynamics) may reflect informed reading rather than new, verifiable evidence; that raises uncertainty about timing and scale.\\n- **Key military-stockpile uncertainty:** Estimates of how much of Iran's arsenal remains vary widely, so predictions about how long attacks can be sustained are speculative and could prove too pessimistic or optimistic.\\n- **No clear nuclear escalation signal:** The piece describes conventional missiles, drones and economic disruption rather than any change in nuclear doctrine or weapons use, limiting immediate nuclear-risk implications.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"(Nuclear) War\",\"slug\":\"nuclear-war\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"8277b133-44f3-4621-b831-f5efaa7a65e7\",\"title\":\"Al-Monitor\",\"displayTitle\":\"Al-Monitor\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Human Development\",\"slug\":\"human-development\"}}},{\"id\":\"7e20655a-075b-4058-9fcf-9a925235978b\",\"slug\":\"brent-tops-100-after-tanker-attacks\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.africanews.com\/2026\/03\/09\/strait-of-hormuz-crisis-war-in-the-middle-east-drives-oil-over-100\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Strait of Hormuz crisis:  War in the Middle East drives oil over $100\",\"title\":\"Brent tops $100 after tanker attacks\",\"titleLabel\":\"Strait tension\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-10T01:01:50.585Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Rising violence around the Strait of Hormuz has driven Brent crude above $100 a barrel as tanker attacks and a partial blockade cut regional tanker traffic by about 90%. The strait normally moves roughly 20% of global oil and gas, prompting market panic, price volatility, and concern that supply shocks could raise fuel and food costs worldwide.\",\"quote\":\"burn any ship\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Senior commander, Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC)\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Africanews reports Brent crude surged past $100 after tanker attacks and a near-blockade of the Strait of Hormuz, cutting ~20% of oil flows and risking global fuel and food price shocks.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Strait shipments cut:** The near-blockade and attacks have collapsed tanker traffic in the Strait of Hormuz, which handles about 20% of global oil and LNG, producing an immediate international supply shock. This is a significant economic disruption affecting hundreds of millions of people through higher transport, heating, and food costs. For example, Kpler reports traffic plunged roughly 90% in a week and Brent jumped 17% to $107 a barrel.\\n- **Direct attacks on shipping:** About ten vessels have been attacked or targeted near the strait, and an IRGC commander threatened to “burn any ship,” which raises the risk of military escalation across the Gulf. That heightens the chance of broader regional conflict that would prolong supply interruptions and deepen international economic effects.\\n- **Global market volatility:** Traders are already pricing in bigger swings, with Brent at its highest since 2022, so short-term financial contagion could ripple through commodity, currency, and stock markets.\\n- **Energy policy and security responses:** Governments may release strategic reserves, reroute shipments, or speed projects to reduce Middle East dependence, changing energy investment and security plans.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Attacks and partial blockade at the Strait of Hormuz curb roughly 20% of oil flows, pushed Brent up 17%, and risk global fuel and food price shocks.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Event may be temporary:** Price spikes often reflect panic and can reverse if diplomacy or alternative supplies restore flows; a short-term disruption does not guarantee long-term change. For instance, Iran's foreign minister publicly said Tehran had “no intention” of closing the strait, creating scope for de-escalation.\\n- **Conflicting statements increase uncertainty:** Mixed official messages (threats from a commander versus diplomatic denials) make it unclear whether the blockade will stick, so projected impacts may be overestimated.\\n- **Impact uneven across populations:** Higher fuel and food prices hit poorer countries and vulnerable households harder, while wealthy states and firms can buffer shocks, limiting uniform global harm.\\n- **Early news snapshot:** This is breaking news reporting on a fast-moving situation, so later facts (scale, duration) may change and revise the significance assessment.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"af432873-d571-4184-a1b5-977054d2d38c\",\"title\":\"africanews\",\"displayTitle\":null,\"issue\":{\"name\":\"General News\",\"slug\":\"general-news\"}}},{\"id\":\"f3689057-a498-4847-bfc0-a8b3a8fbd8b2\",\"slug\":\"saudi-warns-iran-threatens-retaliation-and-us-base-use\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/kathmandupost.com\/world\/2026\/03\/08\/saudi-has-told-iran-not-to-attack-it-warns-of-possible-retaliation\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Saudi has told Iran not to attack it, warns of possible retaliation\",\"title\":\"Saudi warns Iran, threatens retaliation and US base use\",\"titleLabel\":\"Gulf conflict\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-09T01:03:12.099Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":6,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Saudi Arabia told Iran it prefers diplomacy but warned that continued strikes on Saudi territory and energy sites could force Riyadh to allow US forces to use Saudi bases and to retaliate. Iran’s president apologized to neighbours, yet Iran’s military command still calls US and Israeli assets primary targets amid ongoing Gulf strikes.\",\"quote\":\"if Iranian attacks persisted against Saudi territory or energy infrastructure, Saudi Arabia would be forced to permit US forces to use their bases there for military operations.\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Original article\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Kathmandu Post reports Saudi warned Iran to stop strikes, saying it could retaliate and allow US forces to use Saudi bases — raising the risk of wider Gulf escalation and energy disruption.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Risk to global energy supplies and markets:** This story threatens a major source of global oil and gas because attacks on Gulf energy infrastructure can sharply reduce output and spike prices; that would have a moderate regional-to-global impact, affecting millions through higher fuel and transport costs. The mechanism is direct damage to facilities or the need to halt exports, and Gulf states collectively supply a large share of global oil flows.\\n- **Regional military escalation:** The warning increases the chance of a wider war involving Iran, Gulf states, the US and Israel, which is a moderate-to-significant geopolitical impact that could persist for months. If fires draw in external forces or permit US operations from Saudi bases, fighting could spread beyond current actors and infrastructure targets.\\n- **US-Saudi security alignment:** Riyadh saying it may permit US use of bases signals deeper military cooperation that can change operational options and deterrence in the region.\\n- **Civilian and infrastructure harm:** Reported strikes already hit civilian targets and critical infrastructure, raising immediate humanitarian and economic harms for local populations.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"Saudi warning raises risk of wider regional war that could disrupt Gulf energy exports and global markets, but escalation and long-term effects remain uncertain.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Sourcing and uncertainty:** The core warning is reported via unnamed sources and may represent a diplomatic message rather than a firm policy change, so the facts and intent could shift quickly based on private talks or backchannels.\\n- **Diplomatic de-escalation signals:** Iran’s president publicly apologized and Tehran reported suspending attacks on neighbouring states, which could reduce short-term escalation risk and limit long-term impact.\\n- **Regional, not global, direct effects:** Most direct effects are concentrated in the Gulf and nearby states; any broader global consequences depend on secondary channels like energy markets.\\n- **Fast-moving situation:** This is an evolving news item where subsequent actions (new strikes, diplomatic deals, or restraint) will materially change relevance.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"c7e2b91e-011a-4ac1-bf41-25a2a918181a\",\"title\":\"Kathmandu Post\",\"displayTitle\":\"Kathmandu Post\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Planet & Climate\",\"slug\":\"planet-climate\"}}},{\"id\":\"e2b5b07e-b2bd-4c84-ae71-ba772e7816c1\",\"slug\":\"trump-calls-oil-spike-a-small-price-for-iran-action\",\"sourceUrl\":\"https:\/\/www.al-monitor.com\/originals\/2026\/03\/trump-defends-iran-war-decision-oil-soars-above-100\",\"sourceTitle\":\"Trump defends Iran war decision as oil soars above $100\",\"title\":\"Trump calls oil spike a small price for Iran action\",\"titleLabel\":\"Nuclear risk\",\"dateCrawled\":\"2026-03-09T01:02:00.817Z\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-10T02:15:00.726Z\",\"status\":\"published\",\"relevancePre\":7,\"relevance\":5,\"emotionTag\":\"scary\",\"summary\":\"Oil topped $100 a barrel as Middle East fighting halted traffic through the Strait of Hormuz and cuts in Gulf output raised supply fears. President Trump called the spike a ‘small price’ to eliminate Iran’s nuclear threat, while U.S. officials weigh sanctions relief for Russian oil and a $20 billion reinsurance plan for Gulf shipping.\",\"quote\":\"Short term oil prices, which will drop rapidly when the destruction of the Iran nuclear threat is over, is a very small price to pay for U.S.A., and World, Safety and Peace\",\"quoteAttribution\":\"Donald Trump, US President\",\"marketingBlurb\":\"Al‑Monitor reports oil topped $100 as Strait of Hormuz traffic halted; Trump calls the spike a 'small price' to eliminate Iran's nuclear threat, but mitigation lowers long-term disruption risk.\",\"relevanceReasons\":\"- **Scale of the conflict and supply disruption:** The war has halted most traffic through the Strait of Hormuz and sent Brent and WTI up over 15 percent, a development with significant regional impact and potential global economic effects. This matches a level where geopolitical events can disrupt markets and raise the risk of wider instability. For example, 20 percent of global oil flows normally transit the strait, and Gulf producers are already cutting output.\\n- **Changes in geopolitical and policy posture:** The U.S. presidential rhetoric and administration moves (considering lifting Russian oil sanctions and creating a $20 billion reinsurance mechanism) signal shifts in policy that could reshape alliances and energy flows. These actions amount to major diplomatic and economic adjustments rather than small, routine measures.\\n- **Risk of escalation to larger military conflict:** Israeli strikes on fuel depots in Tehran and halted maritime traffic increase the chance of wider retaliation and a larger regional war, a development that raises short- to medium-term security risks.\\n- **Global energy market shock and economic ripple effects:** A sustained price spike above $100 would raise fuel costs for millions, feed into inflation, and strain economies, especially ahead of elections in energy-importing countries.\",\"relevanceSummary\":\"A regional war has pushed oil above $100 and could cause short-term global supply shocks, but mitigations and Iran’s modest 4% share reduce long-term systemic risk.\",\"antifactors\":\"- **Political rhetoric and biased framing:** Key claims come from political leaders making strategic arguments, not independent evidence, so statements about duration and necessity of war are uncertain and reflect political goals. This reduces confidence that the reported consequences and benefits are accurately judged.\\n- **Short-term uncertainty about supply disruption:** Markets often overshoot on early conflict news; officials argue disruptions could last weeks, not months, so the shock may be temporary rather than systemic.\\n- **Limited share of global oil from Iran:** Iran supplies roughly 4% of world oil, so losses there alone are unlikely to cause a prolonged global shortage if other producers increase output or buyers shift sources.\\n- **No new, verifiable evidence of imminent nuclear exchange:** The article reports strikes and rhetoric rather than confirmed steps toward nuclear use, limiting the immediate risk of an existential escalation.\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"(Nuclear) War\",\"slug\":\"nuclear-war\"},\"feed\":{\"id\":\"8277b133-44f3-4621-b831-f5efaa7a65e7\",\"title\":\"Al-Monitor\",\"displayTitle\":\"Al-Monitor\",\"issue\":{\"name\":\"Human Development\",\"slug\":\"human-development\"}}}],\"total\":429,\"page\":1,\"pageSize\":25,\"totalPages\":18}"
